@@yThe Gloamvault of Kel'Shadra@@N

@@eBefore the founding of Midgaard's First Stone Accord, disputes were settled
by spoken oath alone. Oaths existed in the memory of the living and died
with them. Inheritance collapsed when witnesses died of plague. Trade
agreements evaporated when oathkeepers were killed. The consequences of
unrecorded oaths were catastrophic and mundane in equal measure.@@N

@@dThe Kel'Shadra Order arose to correct this failure. Vault-Mother Hesparine
introduced the triune doctrine: @@y'What is witnessed must be named; what is
named must be offered; what is offered must be bound.'@@d Cemetery chaplains
and funeral archivists carried chained codices between settlements, witnessing
oaths and certifying burials. The neutrality of the recorder was the system's
founding strength.@@N

@@yThe Gloamvault was built as this doctrine's architectural expression beneath
Midgaard's civic shell. Its bells regulated institutional rhythm. Its ash
liturgy processed confession. Its reliquary knights guarded the physical
testimony that bound the living to the dead.@@N

@@rBut when Kel'Shadra's records became legally and economically authoritative,
power learned to weaponize the archive. Testimony preservation became
testimony control. The institutional motto shifted from 'Last Witness' to
'Last Authority.' Under Velastra and the Veiled Office, approved narratives
were processed quickly while dangerous truths were delayed, partitioned, or
recursively reviewed until resistance decayed.@@N

@@eThe Night of Unsounded Bells marks the catastrophic fracture. Reform clerks
attempted to publish falsified absolution records. Bell-lines went silent.
Outer doors were sealed. Reliquary units were reassigned from defense to
internal suppression. Contested ledgers were broken into memory shards and
bound to spirit-hosts.@@N

@@dThe Gloamvault is the oldest shadow-archive, still operating inherited
procedures without legitimate sovereign. Its officers execute obsolete duties.
Its records exist but resist retrieval. It is a malfunctioning bureaucracy
with selective teeth, and the institution beneath the institution begins
in its depths.@@N
